=========================================================
OOP INTERVIEW NOTES (INTERVIEW PERSPECTIVE)
Encapsulation | Abstraction | Inheritance | Polymorphism
=========================================================

1. ENCAPSULATION
=========================================================

Definition:
Encapsulation is the process of binding data (variables) and methods
(functions) together into a single unit (class) and restricting direct
access to data using access specifiers.

Achieved Using:
• Class
• private
• protected
• public

Example:

class Employee
{
private:
    int salary;

public:
    void setSalary(int s)
    {
        salary = s;
    }

    int getSalary()
    {
        return salary;
    }
};

Advantages:
• Data Hiding
• Controlled Access
• Better Security
• Easier Maintenance
• Low Coupling

Real World Example:
ATM Machine
You can withdraw money without direct access to bank's internal data.

Interview Questions:

Q1. What is Encapsulation?

Answer:
Wrapping data and functions into a single unit and restricting direct
access to data.

Q2. How is Encapsulation achieved in C++?

Answer:
Using classes and access specifiers.

Q3. Why is Encapsulation important?

Answer:
It provides data hiding, security, controlled access and better
maintainability.

Q4. Does private keyword mean Encapsulation?

Answer:
No.

private is one way to implement Encapsulation.
Encapsulation is a broader concept of bundling data and methods together.

=========================================================
ENCAPSULATION vs DATA HIDING
=========================================================

Encapsulation:
Binding data and methods together.

Data Hiding:
Restricting access to implementation details.

Data Hiding is a subset of Encapsulation.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
=========================================================

Encapsulation is the process of bundling data and functions together and
controlling access to data through access specifiers.

=========================================================
2. ABSTRACTION
=========================================================

Definition:
Abstraction means exposing only essential information and hiding
implementation details.

Achieved Using:
• Abstract Classes
• Pure Virtual Functions
• Interfaces

Example:

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout<<"Circle";
    }
};

Advantages:
• Reduces Complexity
• Improves Security
• Loose Coupling
• Easy Code Changes

Real World Example:
Driving a car.

You know:
• Steering
• Accelerator
• Brake

You don't know:
• Engine internals
• Fuel injection mechanism

Interview Questions:

Q1. What is Abstraction?

Answer:
Showing only necessary information and hiding implementation details.

Q2. How is Abstraction achieved in C++?

Answer:
Using abstract classes and pure virtual functions.

Q3. Why do we need Abstraction?

Answer:
To reduce complexity and hide implementation details.

Q4. Can an abstract class have normal methods?

Answer:
Yes.

Q5. Can an abstract class have constructors?

Answer:
Yes.

=========================================================
ENCAPSULATION vs ABSTRACTION
=========================================================

Encapsulation:
How data is protected.

Abstraction:
What functionality is exposed.

Encapsulation:
Implementation level.

Abstraction:
Design level.

Encapsulation:
Achieved using access specifiers.

Abstraction:
Achieved using abstract classes/interfaces.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
=========================================================

Abstraction means exposing only essential behaviour to the user and
hiding implementation details.

=========================================================
3. INHERITANCE
=========================================================

Definition:
Inheritance is a mechanism in which one class acquires properties and
behaviour of another class.

Syntax:

class Derived : public Base
{
};

Purpose:
Code Reusability and IS-A relationship.

Example:

class Vehicle
{
};

class Car : public Vehicle
{
};

Car IS-A Vehicle.

Types of Inheritance:
1. Single
2. Multiple
3. Multilevel
4. Hierarchical
5. Hybrid

Advantages:
• Code Reusability
• Extensibility
• Easy Maintenance
• Reduced Redundancy

Interview Questions:

Q1. Why do we use Inheritance?

Answer:
To reuse existing code and establish IS-A relationship.

Q2. Difference between IS-A and HAS-A?

IS-A:
Inheritance

Example:
Car IS-A Vehicle.

HAS-A:
Composition

Example:
Car HAS-A Engine.

Q3. Which is preferred in design?

Answer:
Composition over Inheritance.

Because inheritance creates tight coupling.

Q4. Disadvantages of Inheritance?

• Tight Coupling
• Fragile Base Class Problem
• Multiple Inheritance Ambiguity

Q5. What is Protected Access Specifier?

Answer:
Accessible inside class and derived classes but not outside.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
=========================================================

Inheritance allows one class to reuse properties and behaviour of another
class and represents an IS-A relationship.

