4. POLYMORPHISM
=========================================================

Definition:
Polymorphism means One Interface, Multiple Forms.

Types:
1. Compile-Time Polymorphism
2. Runtime Polymorphism

=========================================================
Compile-Time Polymorphism
=========================================================

Achieved By:
• Function Overloading
• Operator Overloading

Resolved By:
Compiler

Example:

add(int,int)
add(double,double)

=========================================================
Runtime Polymorphism
=========================================================

Achieved By:
• Function Overriding
• Virtual Functions

Resolved During:
Execution Time

Example:

class Base
{
public:
    virtual void display()
    {
        cout<<"Base";
    }
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:
    void display() override
    {
        cout<<"Derived";
    }
};

Base* ptr = new Derived;
ptr->display();

Output:
Derived

=========================================================
HOW RUNTIME POLYMORPHISM WORKS INTERNALLY
=========================================================

1. Compiler creates vtable.
2. Every object contains hidden vptr.
3. vptr points to vtable.
4. Function call is resolved at runtime.

This is called Dynamic Dispatch.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is Polymorphism?

Answer:
Ability of an object to take multiple forms.

Q2. Types of Polymorphism?

Answer:
Compile-Time and Runtime.

Q3. Difference between Compile-Time and Runtime Polymorphism?

Compile-Time:
• Function Overloading
• Faster
• Resolved by Compiler

Runtime:
• Function Overriding
• Uses Virtual Functions
• Resolved at Runtime
• Slight Runtime Overhead

Q4. Why are Virtual Functions required?

Answer:
To achieve Runtime Polymorphism.

Q5. Why does Runtime Polymorphism have overhead?

Answer:
Because function resolution happens through vtable/vptr at runtime.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
=========================================================

Polymorphism means one interface can represent multiple implementations.
Compile-time polymorphism is achieved through overloading, whereas
runtime polymorphism is achieved through virtual functions and overriding.

=========================================================
30-SECOND INTERVIEW SUMMARY
=========================================================

Encapsulation:
Bundling data and methods together and controlling access to data.

Abstraction:
Showing only essential information and hiding implementation details.

Inheritance:
Acquiring properties and behaviour of another class to achieve code reuse
and IS-A relationship.

Polymorphism:
One interface with multiple implementations; achieved using overloading
(compile-time) and virtual functions (runtime).
